  "prompt_text": "A chess board has 64 squares. Two opposite corners are removed. Can you cover the remaining 62 squares with dominoes that each cover exactly 2 adjacent squares? Prove your answer.",
  "response_text": "To determine whether it is possible to cover the remaining 62 squares of a chessboard with dominoes after two opposite corners are removed, we can use a coloring argument based on the properties of the chessboard.\n\n### Step-by-Step Analysis\n\n1. **Initial Setup**: A standard chessboard consists of 64 squares, alternating between black and white. When two opposite corners are removed, we remove two squares of the same color (both black or both white). This leaves us with 32 squares of one color and 30 squares of the other color.\n\n2. **Domino Properties**: Each domino covers exactly two adjacent squares, which means each domino will always cover one black and one white square.\n\n3. **Color Counting**: To cover the entire board with dominoes, the number of black and white squares must be equal because each domino uses one square of each color. However, after removing two opposite corners, we have an imbalance of 32 squares of one color and 30 squares of the other color.\n\n4. **Conclusion**: Since it is impossible to pair 32 squares of one color with 30 squares of the other color using dominoes (each domino needs one square of each color), it is not possible to cover the remaining 62 squares with dominoes.\n\n### Final Answer\nIt is not possible to cover the remaining 62 squares of the chessboard with dominoes when two opposite corners are removed.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 7\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 9\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 8\nF (Flexibility): 7\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
